.TH "TEMPORAL.DURATION.ROUND" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.Duration.round \- Temporal.Duration.prototype.round()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]round()\f[B]\f[R] method of \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R]
instances returns a new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object with the
duration rounded to the given smallest unit and/or balanced to the given
largest unit.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
round(smallestUnit)
round(options)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]smallestUnit\f[R]
A string representing the \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] option.
This is a convenience overload, so \f[CR]round(smallestUnit)\f[R] is
equivalent to \f[CR]round({ smallestUnit })\f[R], where
\f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] is a string.
.TP
\f[B]options\f[R]
An object containing some or all of the following properties (in the
order they are retrieved and validated):
.RS
.TP
\f[B]largestUnit\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
Any of the temporal units: \f[CR]\(dqyears\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqmonths\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqweeks\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqdays\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqhours\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqminutes\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqseconds\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqmilliseconds\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqmicroseconds\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqnanoseconds\(dq\f[R], or their singular forms, or the value
\f[CR]\(dqauto\(dq\f[R] which means the largest non\-zero component of
this duration or \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R], whichever is greater.
Defaults to \f[CR]\(dqauto\(dq\f[R].
The result will not contain units larger than this; for example, if the
largest unit is \f[CR]\(dqminutes\(dq\f[R], then \(lq1 hour 30
minutes\(rq will become \(lq90 minutes\(rq.
.TP
\f[B]relativeTo\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A zoned or plain date(time) that provides the time and calendar
information to resolve calendar durations (see the link for the general
interpretation of this option).
Required if either \f[CR]this\f[R] or \f[CR]other\f[R] is a calendar
duration, or \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] is a calendar unit.
.TP
\f[B]roundingIncrement\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A number (truncated to an integer) representing the rounding increment
in the given \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R].
Defaults to \f[CR]1\f[R].
Must be in the inclusive range of 1 to 1e9.
If the smallest unit is hours, minutes, seconds, milliseconds,
microseconds, or nanoseconds, the increment must be a divisor of the
maximum value of the unit; for example, if the unit is hours, the
increment must be a divisor of 24 and must not be 24 itself, which means
it can be 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, or 12.
.TP
\f[B]roundingMode\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
A string representing the rounding mode specifying to round up or down
in various scenarios.
See \f[CR]Intl.NumberFormat()\f[R].
Defaults to \f[CR]\(dqhalfExpand\(dq\f[R].
.TP
\f[B]smallestUnit\f[R] \f[I](optional)\f[R]
Any of the temporal units: \f[CR]\(dqyears\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqmonths\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqweeks\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqdays\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqhours\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqminutes\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqseconds\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqmilliseconds\(dq\f[R], \f[CR]\(dqmicroseconds\(dq\f[R],
\f[CR]\(dqnanoseconds\(dq\f[R], or their singular forms.
Defaults to \f[CR]\(dqnanoseconds\(dq\f[R].
For units larger than \f[CR]\(dqnanoseconds\(dq\f[R], fractional parts
of the \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] will be rounded according to the
\f[CR]roundingIncrement\f[R] and \f[CR]roundingMode\f[R] settings.
Must be smaller or equal to \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R].
At least one of \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] and \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R] must
be provided.
.RE
.SS Return value
A new \f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object, where the largest unit is no
larger than the \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R] option, and the smallest unit is
no smaller than the \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] option.
The fractional parts of the \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] are rounded
according to the \f[CR]roundingIncrement\f[R] and
\f[CR]roundingMode\f[R] settings.
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]RangeError\f[R]
Thrown if any of the options is invalid.
.SH DESCRIPTION
The \f[CR]round()\f[R] method performs two operations: rounding and
balancing.
It does the following:
.IP "1." 3
It makes sure the duration is balanced.
If a component is above its preferred maximum (24 hours per day, 60
minutes per hour, etc.), the excess is carried over to the next larger
unit, until we reach \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R].
For example, \(lq24 hours 90 minutes\(rq becomes \(lq25 hours 30
minutes\(rq if \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R] is \f[CR]\(dqauto\(dq\f[R], and
\(lq1 day 1 hour 30 minutes\(rq if \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R] is
\f[CR]\(dqdays\(dq\f[R].
.IP "2." 3
For all components larger than \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R], they are carried
down into \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R]; for example, \(lq2 hours 30
minutes\(rq becomes \(lq150 minutes\(rq if \f[CR]largestUnit\f[R] is
\f[CR]\(dqminutes\(dq\f[R].
.IP "3." 3
For all components smaller than \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R], they are
carried up into \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] as a fractional part, and then
rounded according to the \f[CR]roundingIncrement\f[R] and
\f[CR]roundingMode\f[R] settings.
For example, \(lq1 hour 30 minutes\(rq becomes \(lq1.5 hours\(rq if
\f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] is \f[CR]\(dqhours\(dq\f[R], and then rounded to
\(lq2 hours\(rq using the default settings.
.PP
Calendar units have uneven lengths.
Their lengths are resolved relative to a starting point.
For example, a duration of \(lq2 years\(rq in the Gregorian calendar may
be 730 days or 731 days long, depending on whether it moves through a
leap year or not.
When rounding to a calendar unit, we first get the exact date\-time
represented by \f[CR]relativeTo + duration\f[R], then round it down and
up according to \f[CR]smallestUnit\f[R] and \f[CR]roundingIncrement\f[R]
to get two candidates.
Then, we choose the candidate according to the \f[CR]roundingMode\f[R]
setting, and finally subtract \f[CR]relativeTo\f[R] to get the final
duration.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Rounding off small units
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] duration = Temporal.Duration.from({ hours: 1, minutes: 30, seconds: 15 });
\f[B]const\f[R] roundedDuration = duration.round(\(dqminutes\(dq);
console.log(roundedDuration.toString()); \f[I]// \(dqPT1H30M\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.SS Avoiding larger units
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] duration = Temporal.Duration.from({
  days: 3,
  hours: 1,
  minutes: 41,
  seconds: 5,
});
\f[B]const\f[R] roundedDuration = duration.round({ largestUnit: \(dqhours\(dq });
console.log(
  \(gaTime spent on this problem: ${roundedDuration.toLocaleString(\(dqen\-US\(dq, { style: \(dqdigital\(dq })}\(ga,
);
\f[I]// Time spent on this problem: 73:41:05\f[R]
.EE
.SS Rounding to a whole number of hours
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] duration = Temporal.Duration.from({ days: 1, hours: 1, minutes: 30 });
\f[B]const\f[R] roundedDuration = duration.round({
  largestUnit: \(dqhours\(dq,
  smallestUnit: \(dqhours\(dq,
  roundingMode: \(dqfloor\(dq,
});
console.log(roundedDuration.hours); \f[I]// 25\f[R]
.EE
.SS Rounding by 15\-minute increments
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] duration = Temporal.Duration.from({ hours: 1, minutes: 17 });
\f[B]const\f[R] roundedDuration = duration.round({
  smallestUnit: \(dqminutes\(dq,
  roundingIncrement: 15,
});
console.log(
  \(gaThe queue will take approximately ${roundedDuration.toLocaleString(\(dqen\-US\(dq)}\(ga,
);
\f[I]// The queue will take approximately 1 hr, 15 min\f[R]
.EE
.SS Resolving calendar durations
If either the initial duration or largest/smallest unit contains a
calendar unit, you must provide a \f[CR]relativeTo\f[R] option to
resolve the calendar durations.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] duration = Temporal.Duration.from({ months: 1, days: 1, hours: 1 });
\f[B]const\f[R] roundedDuration = duration.round({
  largestUnit: \(dqdays\(dq,
  smallestUnit: \(dqdays\(dq,
  relativeTo: Temporal.PlainDateTime.from(\(dq2022\-01\-01\(dq),
});
console.log(roundedDuration); \f[I]// \(dqP32D\(dq\f[R]
.EE
.SH SEE ALSO
